}}'''Miguel de Cervantes Saavedra'''{{Ref_label|B|b|none}} ({{IPA-es|miˈɣel ðe θerˈβantes saˈβeðɾa}} in modern [[Spanish language|Spanish]]; September 29, 1547{{ndash}}April&nbsp;23, 1616) was a Spanish novelist, poet, and playwright. His [[Masterpiece|magnum opus]], ''[[Don Quixote]]'', often considered the first [[modern novel]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://books.guardian.co.uk/review/story/0,12084,1105510,00.html |title=Harold Bloom on Don Quixote, the first modern novel &#124; Books &#124; The Gardian |publisher=Books.guardian.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2009-07-18}}</ref> is a classic of [[Western literature]] and is regularly regarded among the best novels ever written. His work is considered among the most important in all of literature.<ref name="Br">{{cite encyclopedia|title=Cervantes, Miguel de|encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Britannica|date=2002}}</ref> His influence on the [[Spanish language]] has been so great that Spanish is often called ''la lengua de Cervantes'' (The language of Cervantes).<ref>{{cite journal|title=La lengua de Cervantes| language =Spanish| url = http://www.cepc.es/rap/Publicaciones/Revistas/2/REP_031-032_288.pdf| publisher =Ministerio de la Presidencia de España|format=PDF| accessdate =2008-08-24}}</ref> He has been dubbed ''el Príncipe de los Ingenios'' - the Prince of Wits.
Cervantes was born at [[Alcalá de Henares]], the fourth of seven children of Rodrigo de Cervantes, a surgeon born at Alcalá de Henares, and Leonor de Cortinas (native from [[Arganda del Rey]]). Cervantes' parents were married in 1543. The family's origins may have been of the minor [[gentry]]. Leonor died on October 19, 1593. The family moved from town to town, and little is known of Cervantes's early years.




